Federal Politics

Justin Trudeau offers provinces billions of dollars for housing — but with strings attached

The federal Liberals will provide $6 billion in new funding for critical water, waste and storm sewer systems and other supports for new housing construction, as long as provinces meet federal requirements for ramping up housing densification, the government says.

Updated April 02, 2024 at 6:46 p.m.
April 2, 2024
April 2, 2024
3 min read

By Tonda MacCharlesOttawa Bureau Chief

OTTAWA—The federal Liberals will provide $6 billion in new infrastructure funding for critical water, waste and storm sewer systems and other supports for new housing construction, as long as provinces meet federal requirements for ramping up housing density, the government says.

In the fourth of a series of pre-budget announcements, Prime Minister Justin Trudeau travelled to Halifax on Tuesday to unveil what he billed as new measures that would “cut red tape, build more homes and help communities grow.”

You are logged in
 Switch accounts

It was met with a wary eye by provinces who were not consulted in advance on the multibillion-dollar announcement that comes with strings attached.

ARTICLE CONTINUES BELOW
ARTICLE CONTINUES BELOW

But the billions were welcomed by the Federation of Canadian Municipalities because cities stand to gain millions directly in new federal funding, even if provinces balk.

Most of the new money— $5 billion — will be tied to provinces agreeing to meet certain conditions, among them allowing construction of fourplex or multiplex townhouses and multi-unit apartments on land that is already owned and serviced without the specific need for municipal approval. That has been a non-starter in Ontario, according to Premier Doug Ford, who recently said his government would not override municipal prohibitions on fourplexes.

“It’s off the table for us,” Ford said last month. “We’re going to build homes, single-dwelling homes, townhomes, that’s what we’re focused on.”

Other conditions that the Trudeau government will demand in federal-provincial agreements to be struck by next year include: a three-year freeze on municipal development fees where local populations are greater than 300,000; accelerated approvals for homes built according to a catalogue of pre-approved designs; and implementation of proposed federal guidelines on protections for homebuyers and renters (which in the latter case were just announced last week). Ottawa’s so-called “bill of rights” for homebuyers would ban blind bidding in housing purchases, and aid renters by requiring disclosure of rental unit pricing histories.

Provinces must also adopt coming changes to the National Building Code to support more accessible, affordable, and climate-friendly housing options, said Housing Minister Sean Fraser.

The remaining $1 billion of the $6-billion infusion for housing infrastructure is to be directed to municipalities in this fiscal year. That is to address “urgent” infrastructure needs that directly create new housing, said Fraser, describing them as shovel-ready projects. They won’t be tied to the same formal conditions as the $5-billion housing infrastructure fund, but Fraser suggested the projects will already be aligned with the main goals.

Trudeau’s government will also top up the existing $4-billion housing accelerator fund — which has been nearly spent or committed — by another $400 million. That money is available to municipalities who agree to fast-track zoning and new home construction.

Fraser said it is “fair” for Ottawa to demand that provinces accept conditions for federal dollars, and if premiers refuse to work with the federal government, “then we’re going to work directly with cities who are willing to implement some of the measures because we want to ensure we’re getting the greatest bang for the buck.”

“We can’t solve the national housing crisis with half measures and doing things the same way they’ve always been done,” he told reporters.

Halifax Mayor Mike Savage, a former Liberal MP who chairs the big city mayors’ caucus at the Federation of Canadian Municipalities, welcomed the announcement alongside Trudeau on Tuesday.

ARTICLE CONTINUES BELOW
ARTICLE CONTINUES BELOW

In an interview with the Star, he said most cities will not balk at Ottawa’s conditions for funding, saying “those are not onerous.” The federal housing accelerator fund has had many of the same conditions and he said “cities were miles ahead of the provinces or the feds” on requiring more density built close to public transit, eliminating requirements for mandatory parking spots around new condos or apartment buildings, or ensuring housing assessments take account of student populations around post-secondary institutions, for example.

    PM Justin Trudeau announces $6-billion infrastructure fund
    Prime Minister Justin Trudeau says the upcoming federal budget will include a $6-billion infrastructure fund to support homebuilding, as well as a $400-million top-up to the housing accelerator fund. During a stop in Dartmouth, N.S. alongside Housing Minister Sean Fraser, Trudeau had to speak over a din from a group of protesters, following allegations that two Indigenous fishermen in Nova...

    As for Ottawa’s decision to insist that fourplexes should be able to be built without special municipal approval — or “as of right” — on land that is already owned and serviced by infrastructure, Savage said cities and provinces have to confront reflexive “NIMBY-ism” (the popular sentiment known as “not in my backyard”) if they are going to meet the challenge of the housing crisis.

    In a written statement, Paul Calandra, Ontario Minister of Municipal Affairs and Housing, said the province awaits more details and is “open to collaboration.”

    “However, we know that local municipalities know their communities best and don’t believe in forcing them to build where it doesn’t make sense. We are here to support municipalities and are giving them the funding and tools that they need to build more housing, of all types,” he said. He cited Ontario’s budget announcement last week of $1.8 billion for housing-related infrastructure, saying, “We are glad to see the federal government finally recognizes this fact.”

    A week ago, all 13 provincial and territorial leaders wrote Trudeau to demand more money and a co-ordinated approach to infrastructure funding.

    ARTICLE CONTINUES BELOW
    ARTICLE CONTINUES BELOW

    Their letter insisted that provinces and territories, not Ottawa, are best placed to understand their “unique regional, municipal and local infrastructure needs.”

    But it’s not clear whether Tuesday’s announcement meets that request.

    Tonda MacCharles is Ottawa Bureau Chief and a senior reporter covering federal politics. Follow her on Twitter: @tondamacc.
